      id: 'cars-p8',
      sectionId: 'cars',
      title: 'Moral Luck and Moral Responsibility',
      passageText: `The concept of moral luck — the idea that factors beyond our control significantly determine the moral judgments we deserve — poses a deep challenge to traditional accounts of moral responsibility. Philosophers such as Kant argued that genuine moral worth depends solely on the will: only what we intend and choose lies within the moral domain. On this view, outcomes shaped by fortune are morally irrelevant; two drivers who behave identically but produce different outcomes due to chance are equally praiseworthy or blameworthy.

Yet our actual moral practices diverge sharply from this Kantian ideal. The driver who happens to strike a pedestrian who unexpectedly steps into the road is treated — legally and socially — as bearing greater responsibility than the driver in identical circumstances who happened not to. This is not an aberration but a pervasive pattern: we judge people by the results of their choices, not merely their intentions, even when those results hinge on factors entirely outside their control.

Thomas Nagel, who coined the term "moral luck" in its modern philosophical usage, identified four varieties: resultant luck (the outcomes of our actions), circumstantial luck (the situations we face), constitutive luck (who we are, including our dispositions and temperament), and causal luck (the prior causes that shaped our choices). The more deeply we examine any dimension of morality, Nagel argued, the more the ground beneath "control" seems to erode — until it seems unclear that we are ever truly responsible for anything.

This leads to what Nagel calls a profound paradox: our ordinary moral practices require both that we hold people responsible and that responsibility requires control. But on examination, control is rarely, if ever, complete. Some philosophers, notably Susan Wolf, have argued that we can preserve meaningful responsibility by focusing on reasons-responsiveness — the capacity to recognize and respond to moral reasons — rather than demanding impossible libertarian free will. Others, following Galen Strawson, maintain that ultimate responsibility is incoherent and that we should revise our practices accordingly. Still others suggest the paradox reveals not that responsibility is illusory but that our concept of control was always too demanding.`,
